Introduction
I took the Certified Kubernetes Administrator (CKA) exam on May 2025. The CKA exam was updated after February 2025, the update came with new topics (like the Gateway API) and very little documentation. That made preparation tricky ‚Äî but also more exciting.


So if you‚Äôre planning to take it soon, you will find in this article the topics that are covered in the CKA exam and the resources that I used to pass with a score of 75%.

The materials I have used
First of all, to be well prepared for the exam you need to be aware of exam topics. Here is the official curriculum to consult before going to the:
Curriculum ‚Üí

10% Storage
15% Workloads and Scheduling
20% Servicing and Networking
30% Troubleshooting
25% Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration
The official CKA course: The study materials provided are comprehensive and granular in nature. You have the option to acquire them as part of your examination package. Nevertheless, I observed that many of the instructional content pieces demand considerable preliminary configuration work before learners can concentrate on their core educational goals. This preliminary setup phase requires substantial time investment and additional work, thereby increasing the difficulty level of the initial learning phase.

Become a member
Mumshad‚Äôs Udemy course: I am highly enthusiastic about endorsing this program. It is captivating, application-oriented, and remarkably accessible to learners. The practical lab exercises are thoughtfully constructed, and the integrated sandbox platforms eliminate configuration barriers, enabling you to immediately engage with the fundamental principles. In educational contexts, when the initial learning experience is straightforward and pleasurable, retention and mastery are substantially enhanced. This program successfully rendered Kubernetes instruction accessible, practical, and thoroughly pleasurable.

